form/theming.html.body:
Theming
Theming a validation type is possible by writing a React Component and registering it in the ComponentRegistry via registerComponent
ComponentRegistry.registerComponent(FieldType.Number, "guided", GuidedNumbersField)

With this we have registered a theme named guided for the Number-FieldType.
To render a number field with said theme pass the theme-property to a SharedField.


 Info: See it in actionClick here to see a live demo of this example field component
This is the code for the registered component.
import * as React from 'react'
import { IFieldProps, ComponentRegistry } from '@xpfw/form-shared'
import { FieldType } from '@xpfw/validate';
class GuidedNumbersField extends React.Component {
  public randomize() {
    this.props.setValue(Math.round(Math.random() * 100))
  }
  public componentWillMount() {
    this.randomize()
  }
  public render() {
    return (

         {
          this.props.setValue(this.props.value - 1)
        }}>Decrease
        Value of {this.props.field.mapTo} is: {this.props.value}
         {
          this.props.setValue(this.props.value + 1)
        }}>Increase {
          this.randomize()
        }}>Randomize

    )
  }
}

form/types.html.body:
Custom Types
xpfw is made to be flexible. Need to validate a type more complex than one of the base ones? Write your own validator!
To do that first register a validator for said type.
After that you can register a themed component for the default-theme of your new type.
import * as React from 'react'
import { IFieldProps, ComponentRegistry } from '@xpfw/form-shared'

class OnlyDividableByThree extends React.Component {
  public render() {
    return (

         {
          this.props.setValue(3)
        }}>Fix Value
        Value of {this.props.field.mapTo} is: {this.props.value}
         {
          this.props.setValue(this.props.value + 1)
        }}>Break Value {
          this.props.setValue(2)
        }}>Randomize

    )
  }
}

ComponentRegistry.registerComponent("mustBe-1", "default", OnlyDividableByThree)

stacks/nedb.html.body:
NeDB
If you want to write an offline application @xpfw/ui-nedb is the adapter you are looking for.
Overwrite the client property of BackendClient and your xpfw powered offline application is ready to go.
import { BackendClient } from '@xpfw/ui-shared';
import NedbClient from '@xpfw/ui-nedb';
BackendClient.client = NedbClient
